<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Wow, thanks for the replies all!  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>The 72 DPS DID factor in Flying Kick, btw.  <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0"><P>Woe...<P>"monk = 129600 dmg<BR>wiz = 79135 dmg"<P>Sweet! That's not quite as disparate as I had imagined.  <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0"> Now, you forgot to factor in one thing--the 45 minutes of downtime the group had to endure trudging back to the dungeon because they chose a monk over a wizard when they got overwhelmed and couldn't evacuate. Oh, and the 15 minutes of downtime caused by resurrection, re-buffing, and getting the cleric back to FoM. Oh, and the 30 minutes or so it will take to regain the experience the group lost. Now let's re-do that efficiency model!  <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0"> EQ is a wacky world, difficult to reduce down to a simple equation.<P>Arlina, the above example is considering an UBER-melee. A majority of level 60 monks don't have the Bo Staff of Trorsmang. Heck, nobody on my server has broken Veeshan's Peak yet (Saryrn). So, tone that figure down to 110,000 for a regular lv 60 monk, maybe 100,000 for a regular lv 60 warrior. It's a wee bit of an exaggeration to say wizards only deal 1/3 of Warrior damage, even in nonstop pulling groups.  <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0"><P>Like I said, in continuous pull groups, wizards are 3rd-rate damage dealers. <P>- Rogues and Monks are the primary damage dealers. <BR>- Warriors, Rangers, Shadow Knights, Paladins, and Pets (if they're an option) are the secondary damage dealers. <BR>- Wizards, Magicians, Necros, Shamans, or Druids (depending on group config, hunting environ) can all be 3rd rate damage dealers. <BR>- Bards are 4th rate damage-dealers (*chuckles* sorry had to toss that in there. ;>... ever seen a bard melee?--wohooo!!)<P>You'll notice the overlapping nature of Mages and Necros. Yes, if pets are an option, Mages and Necros are the damage kings, plain and simple. If they're not (A majority of dungeon hunting, credit poor pathing and shoddy AI), then they're in the 3rd tier along with Wizards.<P>Now...<P>Can a monk root?<BR>Can a monk stun?<BR>Can a monk cast a stackable damage shield? (wiz DS stacks with Mage AND Druid DS)<BR>Can a monk snare?<BR>Can a monk do 2240 damage 14 seconds when necessary? (double-Comet)<BR>Can a monk evacuate the group?<P>Melee is boring--it's plodding, brainless, repetetive damage. Think of the tanks as our slaves. They pull to us, the absorb hits for us, and when they're *lucky* we toss in a nuke or two to help out ("thank you sir--may I have another?"), hehe. But seriously... melee/heal/melee/heal... this is the core *thing* in dungeons. Once you have that covered. You can start getting fancy. You can pull 5 mobs, have the enchanter keep them all mezzed, have the wizard keep them all rooted so they don't jump the chanter when mez breaks, snare them all at once with the wiz, nuke something down FAST when it jumps the healer and won't get off, stun that caster... So many things that a dumb-butt tank cannot do ("AAAHH!! Not a Ranger Nuke!! AHHHH!!") ("AHHH!! I pulled 4 mobs--I guess we're all screwed!") etc etc etc.<P>Here's the schtick--in high-pull groups, wizards' role is NOT to be primary damage dealer in every fight. Once you get over that and can deal with it, you'll start to dig the class. You'll start to appreciate how useful the unique package of things that the wizard has truly is to groups. <P>You sacrifice consistent damage, and in exchange you get:<P>- The speediest damage in the game<BR>- Evacutation insurance<BR>- Root (better than druid/ranger root since it doesn't break mez)<BR>- Stun (any stun is good stun, I have 5 spell-interrupts at lv 51)<BR>- Snare (possibly the single spell that saved our class--Bonds of Force)<BR>- Quad-kiting capabilities. If you haven't given this a shot yet, and you don't have JBoots, partner up with a Druid and have a go at it--the feeling of sheer power is ridiculous... I just hit 51, and I see:<P>You begin casting Pillar of Frost<BR>A Raptor was hit by non-melee for 755<BR>A Raptor was hit by non-melee for 755<BR>A Raptor was hit by non-melee for 755<BR>A Raptor was hit by non-melee for 755<P>I mean... WOW!! 3020 damage for 325 mana, hehe.<P>Lastly, the bind-sight pulling technique... in that spot, you can't get to where you can *see* Xalgoz without walking by several green (at lv 45-or-so) skellies that will attack you. So, you cast Bind Sight on one of the skellies in front of the church. Then, you use F9 to change perspective, navigate around to where you can see Xalgoz, and click on him to get him in your target bar. Once you have him in your target bar, you can nuke from behind the church (this wall you can nuke through for some reason). Voila!  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>Anyway, I'll get off my soap box now, hehe... happy hunting all!<P>--------------------<P>51 Channeller :: Simryd "Your-target-resisted-Tishan's-Clash" L'Drael, Erudite Wizard of Quellious<BR>44 CLE :: Ulanji, High Elf Cleric of Tunare<BR>30 NEC :: Quokuus Jhuoroq, Human Plaguebringer of Bertoxxulous<BR>24 MNK :: Xodien Lo'Jong, Disciple of the Ashen Order<BR>14 SHD :: Sujata, Iksar Dark Knight of Cazic Thule<BR>12 RNG :: Kujatta, Human Patron of the Stormbringer<BR>*****************<BR>:: "Eschew Obfuscation" ::
