To Simryd <P>If you want to make comparisons you cant switch back and forth between perfect situtaions and "real" ( I use the quotation marks to indicate EQ is not real, sometimes I forget LOL   <IMG SRC="biggrin.gif" border="0"> )situations in the game. You were comparing perfect sinarios with no reduced damage for the monk or the wizard. When you saw the wizard still lost damage wise over an hour you want to use real in game situations to add value to the wizard class. Well in the real situation a wizard chain casting would die from the agro generated, he would never get in 3 casts let alone 6 casts before he was beaten do death by the mobs. However the monk can do he 72dps ( reduced for misses and non max damage hits of course ) to every mob for the whole duration of the fight since he is more equiped to handle the mobs agro in the first place. Further more if you had another tank instead of a wizard your group would be less likely to get overwhelmed in the first place. Also you forgot to mention how most group break up after an evac becuase they dont want to spend 45 min trudging back to the dungeon.<P>A note on evacs, they look good on paper but the rarly work out in practice. This is becuase it is hard to get 2 ppl to agree on something let alone 6 ppl. I have never evaced and had all 5 other member be happy that they lived; there is alway at least one who is very vocal about how unhappy he is and thinks we could have survieved the encounter. Also most groups do not want you to evac at all. I have only evaced 5 times total; each time I only did it when someone else in the group asked for it, and all 5 times the group broke up becuase of it. All it take is one or 2 of the key members to quit the group becuase they dont want to fight there way back to the pull spot and the group disapears. In my experiance caster usualy apriciate the evac ( becuase we die so easily ) but tanks and hybrids almost never can agree that an evac was nessasary ( untill the die ofcorse and then they want to know why you didnt evac ).<P>The bottome line when a pick up group is being fromed, the first 4 spots are prity much pre determined if you want to be sucess full.<P>1. Tanks ( a monk or a warrior is prefered ).<BR>2. Healer ( cleric is prefered )<BR>3. Mana Regenerator ( Enchanter is prefered )<BR>4. Buffer ( Shamen is best buffer, but a druid can buff and act as a secondary healer )<P>Now the other 2 spots could be filled in by just about any class becuase you already have the main components of a sucessfull group, how ever if you want to be most efficent you will get two more tanks.<P>5. ) Depends on what you got for you number one tank. If you got a warriorfor defence then get a monk for pulling. If you started with a monk, get a warrior.<P>6. ) Rogue for fast and masive damage damage.<P>You could also use hybrids for the 5 and 6 spots, but they will be less effective than pure tanks. <P>Do you notice what is not mentioned in these group compositions?<P>Its the wizard, mag and necro. They do not add to a group, they reduce efficency and leach mana from the healer and buffer that could be better used on a tank. They dont do enough damage to pay for there up keep. <P>The only reason to invite a wizard is if your group can alreay more than handle any mob you are pulling and you just them to speed up fights. The only problem with this is that the wizard does not speed up fights enough to make up for the exp he draining from the group on every pull ( with his down time he is actually slowing down the rate you get exp over a one hour time frame). Even in this situation you would be better off just leaving an open spot than inviting a wizard.<P>By the way thank you for you response to my post on wizard ballance, I added the site you listed to my favorites list.  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0">
