<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Very good post Bael.<P>We have to remember--when a tank is dealing damage in a group, his contribution must be divided by 2 (assuming a 1:1 ratio of melee:healers). Why? Becase all the damage he is contributing requires 2 people--himself, and the healer to support him. A wizard's damage is for him and him alone. So, you have to factor that in. <P>I've chosen to sum it up by the following equation (here we go again!! wohooo!!)  <IMG SRC="biggrin.gif" border="0"><P>To "pull his weight," a Wizard only has to do [T/(T + H))] times the average damage output of all the tanks within a group with H healers, and T tanks.<P>1 healer and 1 tank...<BR>[1/(1+1)] = 1/2 or 50% of the average tank damage.<P>1 healer and 2 tanks...<BR>[2/(2+1)] = 2/3 or 67% of the average tank damage.<P>1 healer and 3 tanks...<BR>[3/(3+1)] = 3/4 or 75% of the average tank damage.<P>Food for thought!  <IMG SRC="biggrin.gif" border="0">
</FONT>
