<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Something I left off.<P>When people read this, they will say "sure, that's how it should be, Wizards should do more damage than anyone else per second.  I agree, this is a good thing."<P>In your analysis, at level 60 (ignoring all previous levels, where, for example at level 59, the Wizard doesn't DO 170 dps, and the monk does his damage still; and ignoring rogues can and will actually outdamage monks), the Monk does 72 dps and the Wizard does 170.<P>Now, this looks good initially, when you examine the classes and think "that's neat, the Wizard does about 2 1/2 times the damage, he's contributing well!"<P>But there's a problem, and that is what's being left out of this optomistic analysis:<P>Aggro and mana cost.  IF a Wizard chain casted doing this damage level in a fight, then they would quickly be summoned and killed, or if by some bizarre incredible gap in coding and programming bug the Wizard DID NOT get obliterated, they are out of mana in about half a dozen casts (depending how well equipped and how many specialization checks went well).<P>The Aggro means the Wizard can NOT cast continuously like this, and as such can NEVER give the damage per second ratio that you suggest.  Due to the need to control aggro and actually remain BELOW the warrior taunt level, Wizards have to refrain from casting for long periods of time, and use less powerful blasts to try to contribute.<P>When the Wizard is out of mana he contributes NOTHING to the group, absolutely zero, zip, nada, which means his contribution WITH mana has to be so significant that it makes up for this total lack of action.<P>So we come down to the Wizard doing much less, probably a third that damage per second because he can't cast his biggest blast EVERY SECOND to kill the monster.  I left off fizzles and resists totally with this example, because I'm leaving off misses and assuming max damage for the monk too.<P>Now does the Wizard doing about 55 dps sound reasonable and good to everyone?  Simryd?  Because that's closer to what he'll actually contribute.  Then when he's out of mana he contributes ZERO damage per second.<P>Meanwhile, the Monk is tearin away, he does 72 dps in this ideal examination because that's all monks do in a fight, hit things, and they don't stop until they are dead or feign death.  Since they don't do catastrophic damage in one horrendous burst, and have higher hps, AC, and damage avoidance than a Wizard, they are not nearly as affected by aggro as the Wizard.<P>And when the Wizard meditates, the Monk continues to hit the target for 72 dps.<P>55 vs 72.  0 vs 72.  Does this look fine to you?<P>By the way, that same Wizard at level 59 using his best spell and in the magical faerie tail world of no aggro etc does a whopping 132 damage per second with Lure of Frost.<P>Give a level 30 monk his best weapons and haste and see how much damage he does?  The Wizard never EVER can do more DPS than his spells dictate, twinking does NOTHING for that.
</FONT>
