""Second... aggro. They should put the following on page 1 of the EQ manual--"If you are going to nuke a monster, wait until it is half dead prior to casting.""<P>"And how, precisely, is that different than what I said?"<P>It's not. I re-read your post, and we're on the same page here. Sorry for misinterpreting. I was feeling a bit hostile after being accused of grouping with idiots.<P>"Your DPS has been reduced by waiting all that time, hasn't it? You had all that time to cast and DID NOT which means you did no damage per second whatsoever."<P>Yes, which is why I wrote...<P>"The insane DPS of wiz nukes is usually important on mobs that need to die, and die now, and we didn't realize it until just now due to a couple of adds..."<P>Here's what I mean--your group is killing something, and suddenly several mobs jump in (via train, pop, roamer, whatever). NOW is when DPS really matters. You have to get through the next series of fights ASAP, after which you'll have time to recover. A monk, warrior, or whoever else is capped far under 100 DPS. A wizard can double their DPS in THAT timeframe--i.e. the time when DPS SUDDENLY MATTERS. In critical situations like this, the high DPS doubles both as damage-dealing and damage prevention--dead mobs can't hurt you. <P>Of course... each time you need to wait for tank-aggro to build up. However, you seem to think that this implies that a wizard will never be able to surpass tank damage without being aggroed... which is not true from my experience. This is why I wrote:<P>"When both a warrior and a rogue have been working a mob down to half, and you chain cast Ice Comet (or draught or whatever else), you will likely end up dealing THE MOST damage. However, the mob will never jump you. "<P>Well, maybe sometimes it will... but not usually, from my experience.<P>At the core of this idea is the following thesis: "While a wizard has mana, his group is capable of significantly higher short-term DPS than the group would be if it had a melee class instead of the wizard." It's all about having the *ability* to pull out the stops when needed. Not residing in a continuous state of a nuking extravaganza.<P>Let me know if I can explain this point any better.<P>"Further, burning something dead that is snared is idiotic and a waste of mana, its just standing there LET IT DIE."<P>Agreed. However, until it's given up the fight, it keeps on fighting even when snared. The faster you can get it to it's "running-for-my-life" mentality, the better... no? I almost NEVER cast a killing nuke. Ever. Exceptions being room-breaks and the like.<P>"Lastly, if you wait til the monster is half dead before casting you not only look useless to the group but you aren't stunning when you should, will use up your mana too fast (cast cast cast cast ok guys LOM gotta med through this fight), and lastly by doing that you still don't neccessarily control aggro... they might still turn on you as Im sure you know."<P>If I a mob is slowed, I almost never stun, unless it's a caster. Otherwise, I do stun from time to time for dmg prevention. <P>I can toss in 2 draughts on most every pull, sometimes a draught and a Comet or 3 draughts. Yes, on most of the stuff we pull, I'm being outdamaged by the Rogue and Warrior in my group. However, on room-break situations, I ALWAYS outdamage everyone on the first several mobs to help spread out room pops. I might get jumped *occasionally* by monsters that earn 4 or 5 draughts, but it's never a big deal--at most one round of melee and the warrior has him off me. Anyway, there's yet another situation for you where wizards outshine melee--*control*. We can decide which mobs die when and how quickly, by virtue of our nukes (yes, I am aware that other casters can do this too, but this whole series of threads seems geared to pit melee vs. wizard).<P>"Saying a Wizard with out any DD would be useful to a group is the most patently idiotic thing I have ever laid eyes on."<P>IF snare is useful, THEN any class that can cast snare is useful. Note--I am not saying MORE useful than other snaring classes with all their spells. I'm just saying, "useful." If you had 5 non-snaring people in a group, none of whom could snare, and you found some strange person who could ONLY snare and do nothing else, that person would be of great value to the group. Am I wrong? Would you keep the "snare-only" person out of your group if your group couldn't snare and there was nobody else around? Of course not. Therefore, snaring is important enough to warrant doling 1/6 of a group's experience to that function alone if need be.<P>"...How many classes have snare? Druid, Ranger, Necromancer, Shadow Knight, Bard, Wizard. Dang, that snare is sure gonna turn the day huh?"<P>YES it will! First off, necro and SK snares do damage, so they are less useful than the rest (mez break). Secondly, it may sound far-fetched, but sometimes there are no Druids, Rangers, or Bards around! If you're there, and they aren't, then you will be highly needed. Am I right?<P>"...HOw bout root? ALL those classes but bard have root, plus Enchanter, Magician (through pet), Cleric, Paladin, hell even melee classes can root and snare through items and poisons."<P>Yes. And all those things are useful. I was merely trying to emphasize, by means of an absurd extreme, that wizards are useful simply by virtue of the fact that they can *have* these useful spells. I was not attempting to say that they are more or less valuable than the other classes that share these spells. (although wizards are the only class that has both a non-damaging snare AND a non-damaging root, hehe  <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0"> )<P>"I agree Wizards aren't broken but you are trying to say the damage level is fine, and its not."<P>Pre-49 I agree with you Mandingo--the damage level needs some work. Post-50 looks better so far. Check back with me in 9 levels though, hehe  <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0"><P>"You are trying to say the Wizard brings so much to a group and they DON'T."<P>'Tis truly a matter of opninion. Personally, I think that any class that can bring snare, root, spell-interruption, evacuation, and the fastest & most efficient direct damage spells in the game to a group is bringing a good deal of usefulness. Your opinion seems to be that all of this amounts to zilch. I think it amounts to [(7+zilch)/((squat+2)*27)], or 61. 61... now that's deep.  <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0"><P>Paz.<P>--------------------<P>51 Channeller :: Simryd "Your-target-resisted-Tishan's-Clash" L'Drael, Erudite Wizard of Quellious<BR>44 CLE :: Ulanji, High Elf Cleric of Tunare<BR>30 NEC :: Quokuus Jhuoroq, Human Plaguebringer of Bertoxxulous<BR>24 MNK :: Xodien Lo'Jong, Disciple of the Ashen Order<BR>14 SHD :: Sujata, Iksar Dark Knight of Cazic Thule<BR>12 RNG :: Kujatta, Human Patron of the Stormbringer<BR>*****************<BR>:: "Eschew Obfuscation" ::
