"Of course... each time you need to wait for tank-aggro to build up. However, you seem to think that this implies that a wizard will never be able to surpass tank damage without being aggroed."<P>Not from my experience either, and I didn't suggest that.  I said sometimes even if you DO wait sometimes the monsters will aggro on you, I think it is the same wierd glitch that makes some monsters randomly aggro on someone and NEVER turn away.<P>"At the core of this idea is the following thesis: "While a wizard has mana, his group is capable of significantly higher short-term DPS than the group would be if it had a melee class instead of the wizard." It's all about having the *ability* to pull out the stops when needed. Not residing in a continuous state of a nuking extravaganza."<P>I agree, the Wizard is wonderful at bringing the boom down fast.  The problem is this: How often is that needed, and when it is needed, how often is it even feasible?  If you are in an emergency, you are in an emergency - no waiting half the life of the target to nuke.  And Aggro + resistances makes even this task a questionable thing.<P>The question then becomes, "Is this a viable class design?" and I really can't say yes to that.<P>"Anyway, there's yet another situation for you where wizards outshine melee--*control*. We can decide which mobs die when and how quickly, by virtue of our nukes (yes, I am aware that other casters can do this too, but this whole series of threads seems geared to pit melee vs. wizard)."<P>Other classes actually do it better, and they handle emergencies better.  Who would you rather have for control and breaking a room: Wizard or Enchanter?  And since emergencies and control is the basis of your entire defense of the class design, that is a problem, isn't it?<P>"IF snare is useful, THEN any class that can cast snare is useful."<P>Not if that's what they bring exclusively.  I know you were overstating to make a point but really, come on  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>"YES it will! First off, necro and SK snares do damage, so they are less useful than the rest (mez break). Secondly, it may sound far-fetched, but sometimes there are no Druids, Rangers, or Bards around! If you're there, and they aren't, then you will be highly needed. Am I right?"<P>Problem is darkness doesn't do damage.  It's just a fancy snare, yeah I used to think it was a DOT too, but its not.<P><BR>""I agree Wizards aren't broken but you are trying to say the damage level is fine, and its not.""<P>"Pre-49 I agree with you Mandingo--the damage level needs some work. Post-50 looks better so far. Check back with me in 9 levels though, hehe"<P>I think it depends on where you hunt.  But there is this problem: The game is designed where the higher level you get, the weaker you are, relative to the monsters.  As a result, as you get higher and higher level, you do less and less damage to the bad guys.  Now, everyone else does this, but they compensate in a wide variety of ways.  But the WIzard has one way of doing damage to a monster: Blasting it.  And since this doesn't persist and eats mana every time, your contribution actually goes down bit by bit.  This is the core of the enraged posts on the general discussion board where people were asking what, exactly, a damage caster was supposed to do on something with more than 100,000 hit points?<P>Monsters get more and more resistances, and they all summon.  This is why Wizards use an AE Rain spell to desparately attempt to make up for the low damage output, because Tears of Druzzil (for example) outdamages Ice Comet if even 2 waves hit.  The post 50 game is really screwed up for all classes but 3: Rogues, Warriors, and Clerics.  Enchanters and Shamans are along as buff vendors, and that's it.<P>"Personally, I think that any class that can bring snare, root, spell-interruption, evacuation, and the fastest & most efficient direct damage spells in the game to a group is bringing a good deal of usefulness. Your opinion seems to be that all of this amounts to zilch." <P>No I think it amounts to not enough for a valid class design.  I don't think a Wizard is useless, I think the class is sub par and needs work.  Not a LOT of work, but a lot of little things that amounts to something big.  There are more little annoying things wrong with this class than any in the game, and the reason is simple: Verant doesn't wanna hear about it.<P>Wizards start out weak and end up roughly the same as everyone else, that's crappy design in a game that is allegedly supposed to be balanced.<P>Wizards have several minor tools, its true, but they are easily replaced by one class: Druid.  And since the Druid can nuke nearly as well as a Wizard in 99% of the situations, PLUS they bring so much more to the group I see a real problem.<P>I think Wizards are almost there.  But I also think they won't ever make it, not ever.<P>"I think it amounts to [(7+zilch)/((squat+2)*27)], or 61. 61... now that's deep." <P>I think that adds up to 42...
