<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
"Yes, that's what i've been saying all along, a tank's damage is NOT his own, it is as much the healer's damage -- a wizard is a self-sufficient, punch-packing, damage-dealing fiend, and pays for the incredible power and self-reliance with downtime... of course with area effect spells however, downtime is irrelevant."<P>That's a nice theory but its unfortunately not true.  Wizards in a group need a tank, healer, and debuffer to be effective.  They aren't any more self sufficient in dealing damage than a Warrior.<P>"But wait!" You say, "what about your soloing!"<P>But that's not damage dealing.  That's movement adjustment.  Wizards can slow their target and not take damage, that's the only reason they can solo.  If they couldn't keep the monster away, they'd die, fast, and bad without any xps past level 5 or so.<P>See people always act as if a cleric healing a tank = a Wizard using mana.  But it doesn't.  First, healing is enormously more mana efficient than damage spells (especially complete heal).  Second, the healer only has to heal ONE tank, not all of them.  There is only one person at a time who will require healing against a given creature.  That means any melee past the first is cake, they are free damage.  Wizards pay for their damage each squeeze of the trigger.<P>And finally there's this: Twinking allows melee classes to increase their damage and use to the group exponentially.  Put the best twink gear in the hands of a Warrior, do the same for a Wizard.  The Warrior just got several factors more powerful, the Wizard does EXACTLY the same damage per second that he did before.  In fact, due to the way mana and stats work for casters, he doesn't have that much more mana.<P>And this means the things that are making problems for high level Wizards are making them MUCH worse for low level WIzards.  That level 20 Wizard who things he's hot stuff with a 169 point blast (when it lands)?  The Warrior next to him can do that much in the 14.8 seconds it takes to cast the next big blast, easily.  In fact with crits and huge weapons, he can do nearly 150 damage in one flurry of attacks.<P>This is where it all comes together: there's a problem at the highest levels with titanic hit point monsters; there are problems at higher levels because of damage per second, and there's problems at the very start because of twinking.<P>And the band plays on....
</FONT>
